{
  "texts": [
    "Building on Allan Turing's work On Computable Numbers (1937), McCulloch's and Pitt's foundations-laying paper A Logical Calculus of the Ideas Immitent in Nervous Activity (1943) set a path to describe cognitive functions in abstract terms showing that simple elements connected in a network can have a huge computational capacity.",
    "Building upon \"the founding fathers´\" achievements, the idea of GAN copes with evolutionary biology principle of an arms race between two species.",
    "Two neural networks contest with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one agent's gain is another agent's loss.",
    "The core principle of a GAN is an \"indirect\" training through the discriminator -competitive network agent that can tell how \"realistic\" the input seems, which itself also updates dynamically.",
    "This means that the generator gets no training to minimize the distance to a specific image, but rather to fool the discriminator."
  ]
}